  "method": "We propose Skill-Sliced, Confidence-Weighted Distillation (S2CWD): an end-to-end pipeline that identifies the subset of a large generalist’s competencies that actually help on the target domain, and transfers them into a compact specialist via hypernetwork-generated adapters trained under multi-granularity supervision. The pipeline has four stages: (1) capability discovery and selection from the generalist, (2) parameter-efficient student architecture with skill adapters, (3) structured, multi-objective distillation with width-slicing, and (4) data-mix reweighting and deployment policy.\n\nStage 1 — Capability discovery and selection: Run the generalist on a specialist development set to extract per-instance signals: logits, intermediate features, optional expert/router activations (if MoE), and a calibrated confidence for each prediction. Treat candidate “skills” as teacher sub-components (experts/layers/prompts) or elicitation modes (instruction templates). Score each skill on (i) relevance to the specialist task and (ii) complementarity to already chosen skills. Formulate skill set selection as greedy maximization of a submodular objective that rewards relevance and diversity; use the teacher’s confidence to weight instance contributions and optionally discard low-confidence transfer signals. This yields a compact, diverse bank of K skills to transfer, avoiding negative transfer from weak or redundant teacher components.\n\nStage 2 — Student with hyper-adapter skill bank: Start from a small specialist backbone and insert lightweight adapters (e.g., LoRA/adapter blocks and attention prefixes) at a few layers. Rather than training a separate adapter per skill, use a tiny hypernetwork that takes a learned “skill token” (one per selected teacher skill) and generates the adapter/prefix weights on the fly. Inputs that activate different skills thus apply different adapter weights while keeping base parameters mostly frozen. A small routing head selects one or a few skills per instance using student-accessible signals (e.g., input features), defaulting to a static prior if routing is disallowed at inference.\n\nStage 3 — Structured, multi-granularity distillation: Train the student with a composite loss. (a) Confidence-weighted soft distillation: KL between student and teacher logits with temperature scaling, reweighted by the teacher’s calibrated confidence and restricted to the selected skill views. (b) Listwise/structured distillation where applicable (ranking, generation with preference lists): optimize a differentiable listwise loss against teacher-provided orderings or preferences. (c) Language-grounded auxiliaries: attach a small text head and train CLIP-style contrastive and a lightweight generative loss that align inputs with short “capability sketches” (skill- or task-descriptions) derived from the selected skills, anchoring the student’s latent space to portable semantics. (d) Matryoshka width-slicing: apply structured masking so the student is supervised at multiple smaller widths in the same pass, adding explicit losses for each slice to ensure robustness under tight latency budgets.\n\nStage 4 — Data-mix reweighting and deployment: Build a unified training mix from specialist-domain data and a curated, capability-matched subset of generalist data. Compute per-source sampling weights from a balanced dev set by minimizing held-out perplexity/loss under a lightweight interpolation model, then resample accordingly during training. At inference, deploy the smallest width that meets latency, with static hyper-adapter weights materialized for the top-M skills or on-the-fly generation if memory allows. A confidence-aware gate can disable skill adapters on inputs where the student is already certain, preserving efficiency.",
  "rationale": "The core challenge is to import only the useful parts of a strong generalist into a compact model without inheriting its full cost or unrelated behaviors. S2CWD tackles this by first selecting a small, diverse subset of generalist skills that demonstrably transfer on the target domain, explicitly avoiding negative transfer. It then injects those skills through parameter-efficient hyper-adapters, so the small specialist gains targeted capacity where it matters while keeping most weights frozen and latency low.\n\nStructured, confidence-weighted distillation preserves fine-grained teacher behavior (including orderings and preferences) and emphasizes reliable signals, while language-grounded auxiliary objectives provide a modality- and task-agnostic scaffold that helps the compact model retain generalist-style abstractions. Finally, Matryoshka width-slicing ensures the student is accurate even at reduced widths, and data-mix reweighting stabilizes training across domain and capability sources—together delivering a specialist that surpasses its baseline on-domain performance with only the relevant generalist capabilities transferred.",
