  "method": "We propose Targeted Capability Distillation with Scaffolding (TCD-S): a budget-aware teacher–student transfer pipeline that moves only the generalist subskills relevant to a given specialist domain into a compact model. Start with a frozen large generalist teacher T and a small specialist student S. Assemble a modest labeled in-domain set L and a large unlabeled in-domain pool U. First, locate what to transfer: run layer-wise linear probes on T to identify intermediate representations that are maximally predictive of the specialist task, producing a prioritized set of teacher subspaces. Factor S’s representation into a shared capability subspace z_shared and a domain idiosyncrasy subspace z_dom; attach lightweight adapters/prompts on the shared path so z_shared is the receptacle for generalist knowledge while z_dom remains free to capture in-domain quirks.\n\nPerform parameter-efficient transfer into S via three aligned channels. (1) Representation alignment: map S’s z_shared to the probed teacher subspaces using a small set of adapters/prompts trained with a feature-matching loss, and an adversarial discriminator with gradient reversal to make S’s shared features indistinguishable from T’s in-domain features. (2) Prediction distillation: for selected examples, minimize a temperature-scaled KL between S and T, using T’s soft targets (and optional rationales) while preserving S’s domain head for calibration. (3) Uncertainty-guided updates: maintain an EMA of prompt/adapter parameters where the update weights grow with example uncertainty, so the limited capacity is preferentially spent on hard, capability-bearing cases without overfitting to easy ones.\n\nControl teacher budget with an active, two-stage data selection loop. Train a lightweight selector (or use S with a deterministic uncertainty head) to propose \"core\" samples from U that are both uncertain for S and diverse; then request T’s supervision only on this core set. Optionally prioritize samples where T and S disagree. This produces compact, high-leverage supervision batches where T’s generalist strengths matter most. Combine pseudo-labels (high-confidence T) and soft labels (temperature-scaled T) with confidence filtering. Optimize S with a multi-objective loss balancing representation alignment, distillation, and supervised loss on L, and learn the adapters/prompts jointly.\n\nAdopt a scaffolding schedule that gradually removes reliance on T. Early rounds allocate a generous teacher budget and higher distillation weight; subsequent rounds shrink both, and freeze portions of z_shared once alignment stabilizes. Continue fine-tuning z_dom against L to preserve domain idiosyncrasies. Use a held-out evaluation set and external metrics to guard against style-only gains. Stop once S matches or exceeds T’s in-domain accuracy under the target compute envelope. Optionally keep a tiny inference-time fallback: if S’s uncertainty surpasses a threshold and budget allows, route the instance to T; otherwise, run S alone for maximal efficiency.\n\nDeployment consists solely of S plus its small adapters/prompts and an uncertainty head. This design cleanly separates transferred generalist capability (z_shared + adapters/prompts) from specialist nuance (z_dom), concentrates teacher supervision on the most informative in-domain samples, and phases out teacher dependence as S internalizes the relevant skills.",
  "rationale": "The core challenge is to capture only the generalist abilities that help within the specialist’s domain, without bloating the small model. TCD-S addresses this by (a) identifying teacher layers that encode domain-relevant signals via probing, (b) dedicating a compact shared subspace in the student to receive those signals, and (c) using parameter-efficient modules (prompts/adapters) plus adversarial alignment to import the representations rather than wholesale copying. Active, uncertainty-driven selection focuses the limited teacher budget on the few in-domain cases where generalist knowledge actually moves the needle, and confidence filtering prevents propagating teacher mistakes.\n\nA curriculum-like scaffolding then reduces teacher assistance over time, ensuring the student becomes self-sufficient. Finally, explicit uncertainty estimation and external evaluation mitigate self-bias during training and enable an optional, bounded fallback at inference. Together, these design choices transfer the relevant generalist capability into a small specialist that is accurate on its own domain and cheap to run.",
