  "method": "We propose CAGE-KD: Capability-Graph-Gated, EKF-Controlled Knowledge Distillation. The key idea is to first restructure a large generalist’s behavior on the specialist domain into a small, discrete set of transferable micro-capabilities, then equip a compact student with (a) lightweight capability gates that modulate a few late layers using a per-instance global attribute, and (b) a prototype layer that anchors the student’s decision regions around those capabilities. A tiny evidence selector identifies the core, task-relevant evidence from each input; only that evidence conditions the student’s gates and the teacher queries. We distill not only logits but also pairwise preference constraints that capture the generalist’s fine-grained ranking or choice behavior, using O(K) teacher calls over the top-K candidates.\n\nCapability discovery and scheduling are explicit. We build a directed capability graph whose nodes represent prerequisite skills uncovered from the generalist’s behavior under small evidence perturbations (identified by the selector) and its induced preference flips. Rather than running full probabilistic inference on this graph, we train a lightweight Bayesian network over capabilities with a sampling-based gradient estimator; this lets us (i) attribute which capabilities are currently gating performance and (ii) choose, at each step, the cheapest counterfactual intervention (mask/augment a specific evidence fragment) most likely to improve the student. During training rollouts, a pseudo-intervention demonstrator queries the generalist only on those targeted counterfactuals and on adjacent pairwise preferences among the top-K candidates, yielding efficient supervision that emphasizes the capability bottlenecks.\n\nThe student is augmented in two places. First, we add 2–3 late-layer capability gates: a small attention readout over the selected evidence produces a global attribute z_g that multiplicatively modulates those layers and is also fed into the final readout. Second, we insert a prototype discrimination layer before logits: a set of trainable prototypes each corresponds to a capability node, learning a discriminative latent geometry that provides single-pass uncertainty. Training optimizes three losses: (1) a standard KD loss on logits conditioned on the selected evidence; (2) a pairwise ranking loss derived from adjacent-swap constraints over the top-K items; and (3) a capability-consistency loss aligning the prototype activations with the capability BN’s current belief. We treat the adapter and prototype parameters as a controlled dynamical system and update them online with a Kalman-style optimizer that adaptively tunes step sizes to the stochasticity of the teacher signals, ensuring stable, fast convergence under tight query budgets.\n\nTo avoid drifting toward style-only or spurious gains, we integrate capability regression tests into the loop: for a subset of batches, the selector swaps or removes a single core evidence fragment predicted by the capability graph to be necessary/sufficient; the student must flip or preserve its decision accordingly. Failures down-weight the corresponding capability’s supervision and trigger additional pairwise constraints, mitigating self-evaluation bias. At inference, the pipeline uses only the tiny selector, the student with capability gates and prototypes, and no teacher calls; the global attribute and prototype uncertainty act as cheap, per-instance controllers to specialize behavior on the fly, preserving generalist-derived competence where it matters for the domain.",
  "rationale": "CAGE-KD transfers the relevant generalist capability rather than raw outputs by (i) factorizing behavior into a capability graph discovered from counterfactual preference flips on core evidence, (ii) embedding those capabilities directly into the student’s representation via global-attribute gates and capability prototypes, and (iii) scheduling supervision toward the current capability bottlenecks. The pairwise-adjacent preference distillation captures the generalist’s fine-grained rankings with linear query complexity, while the prototype layer provides deterministic uncertainty to weight supervision toward reliable teacher signals and to regularize decision regions around capabilities.\n\nMechanistically, this differs from prior prompt/adversarial or uncertainty-EMA approaches: we use control-theoretic, Kalman-style online updates for stable, budget-aware adaptation; we learn and use a capability Bayesian network with sampling-based gradients to drive targeted counterfactual supervision without full inference; we compress preference structure via efficient adjacent-swap constraints; and we inject a per-instance global attribute to modulate select late layers, avoiding heavy prompts or GRL alignment. The result is a small specialist that retains the generalist’s high-value skills on its domain, with minimal runtime overhead and no dependence on the teacher at inference.",
